ce:section.ce:para:
The XPS spectrum was used to characterize the chemical composition and bonding state of Me-CDs. The full-range XPS spectrum of Q235 carbon steel after immersion in blank and 200 mg/L Me-CDs solution for 24 h were depicted in Fig. 3
                        . The emergence of C, N, O, and Fe elements on the carbon steel surface proved the adsorption of Me-CDs on the surface of carbon steel. Simultaneously, the weak nitrogen peak at around 400 eV was detected in Me-CDs, meaning that the melamine was resoundingly bonded with CDs. To analyze the existence form of elements, the high-resolution XPS spectra of four elements and their fitting results were showed in Fig. 3(c–f). The Fe 2p3/2 spectrum could be divided into four peaks, which distributed at 709.62, 710.73, 711.1 and 712.21 eV (Fig. 3c), in correspondence with iron in the states of FeO/Fe⋯O, Fe2O3, Fe⋯Nx and FeOOH [4,49–51], respectively. The O 1 s spectrum (Fig. 3d) could be split into five peaks at 529.53, 529.9, 530.5, 531.24 and 532.2 eV which are associated with the Fe2O3, FeO/O⋯Fe, FeOOH, CO and C-O bonds [4,51–53]
                        ], separately. For high-resolution C 1 s spectrum at binding energies of 284.6, 285.8, 287.7, 288.3 eV (Fig. 3e) are attributed to CC/CC, CO/CN, CN and OCO/NCO bonds, respectively [5,29]. Meanwhile, the N 1 s fine spectrum as displayed in Fig. 3f, which could be deconvoluted into four peaks at 398.7, 399.4, 399.7 and 400.6 eV, corresponding to NH, N⋯Fe, NC and NC bonds, respectively [5,29,49–50]. The appearance of the peak of N-Fe and Fe-Nx bonds indicated that the partial N atoms in the Me-CDs formed coordination bonds with iron atoms due to the lone pair electrons. These results revealed that the melamine was successfully modified on CDs after the acylation reaction, which was in good agreement with the analysis result of FTIR spectrum and XRD analysis.
